==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wreck
<hw>Wreck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & n.</pos> <def>See 2d & 3d
<er>Wreak</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wreck
<hw>Wreck</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>wrak</ets>, AS.
<ets>wr⟦ae⟧c</ets> exile, persecution, misery, from <ets>wrecan</ets> to
drive out, punish; akin to D. <ets>wrak</ets>, adj., damaged, brittle,
n., a wreck, <ets>wraken</ets> to reject, throw off, Icel.
<ets>rek</ets> a thing drifted ashore, Sw. <ets>vrak</ets> refuse, a
wreck, Dan. <ets>vrag</ets>. See <er>Wreak</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>, and
cf. <er>Wrack</er> a marine plant.]</ety> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>wrack</asp>.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The destruction or injury of a vessel by being cast
on shore, or on rocks, or by being disabled or sunk by the force of
winds or waves; shipwreck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hard and obstinate⟦br⟧
As is a rock amidst the raging floods,⟦br⟧
'Gainst which a ship, of succor desolate,⟦br⟧
Doth suffer <qex>wreck</qex>, both of herself and goods.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Destruction or injury of anything, especially by
violence; ruin; <as>as, the <ex>wreck</ex> of a railroad
train</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>wreck</qex> of matter and the crush of worlds.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Its intellectual life was thus able to go on amidst the
<qex>wreck</qex> of its political life.</q> <rj><qau>J. R.
Green.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The ruins of a ship stranded; a ship dashed against
rocks or land, and broken, or otherwise rendered useless, by violence
and fracture; <as>as, they burned the <ex>wreck</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>The remain of anything ruined or fatally
injured.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To the fair haven of my native home,⟦br⟧
The <qex>wreck</qex> of what I was, fatigued I come.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Goods, etc., which, after a
shipwreck, are cast upon the land by the sea.</def>
<rj><au>Bouvier.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wreck
<hw>Wreck</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wrecked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wrecking</conjf>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To destroy, disable, or seriously damage, as a
vessel, by driving it against the shore or on rocks, by causing it to
become unseaworthy, to founder, or the like; to shipwreck.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Supposing that they saw the king's ship <qex>wrecked</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To bring wreck or ruin upon by any kind of violence;
to destroy, as a railroad train.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To involve in a wreck; hence, to cause to suffer
ruin; to balk of success, and bring disaster on.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Weak and envied, if they should conspire,⟦br⟧
They <qex>wreck</qex> themselves.</q> <rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreck</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Wreck
<hw>Wreck</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To suffer wreck or
ruin.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To work upon a wreck, as in saving property or
lives, or in plundering.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wreckage</ent>⟦br⟧
